"Black and White, Dark and Light, see me not, within your sight."

Extremely rare, master smiths of far away notions copied the design from weapons taken from fallen Kara-Turan soldiers. The unusual weapons were carried by high ranking court assassins, and those that knew the meaning of the blade, and saw it drawn, usually did not live long enough to tell about it. Imbued with both forces of life, there is a balance to the blade that slips in, unnoticed, until it is too late.

A ranger with brown hair and a scar across her left cheek.

Helms such as these have only recently begun to surface in the region, however they look ancient. Relics of an old war, long forgotten and a time nearly lost, these powerful artifacts were likely worn by the champions or paragons of the people that created them.

While the original creators of these helms seem to remain unknown, they do bare an uncanny resemblance to the natives of the Mylock Hills.

Stories speak of a poor traveller, victim to a snowstorm one winter night. In the midst of frostbite and unconsciousness, he stumbled upon an isolated monastery, dedicated to Ilmater. The monks took him in, gave him shelter, food and most notably, a pair of thick, snow-wading boots.

With new-found vigor, he left the next day, boots firmly clad. Winter gave way to spring, and spring gave way to further winters, until the man was wealthy enough to return to that secluded monastery, to give his thanks for supporting him at his time of need.

To his surprise, he could not find the monastery, no matter how hard he searched the land. The blizzard returned once more during his searches, covering the land in a white blanket. One quiet night resting in his makeshift shelter, he found a dying man, frozen half to death. After feeding him and nursing him to health, he gifted the man those same boots he received years prior, and decided to build a small monastery in place of the one he could no longer find.

In some circles of nature, a somber tradition prevails. At the passing of an agent, when their time has ultimately come, it is not uncommon that their animal companion should die with them out of supposed grief. To this end, many workers of the natural world have seen fit to burn both master and beast upon the funeral pyre, together.

From their ashes, a Great Druid then crafts a charm to be passed on to others within the circle. The bond between the two survives even in death, and their kinship empowers those who have followed in their footsteps.

The tales of these rings inevitably lead back to the Shadow Plane, though there the trail runs cold. Most local explanations will center around Shadowscape, one of exceedingly few hospitable places in the realm.

Some have held that Grandmistress Luriko of the Three Steps Academy distributes them to students who show promise. Many have suggested they were crafted at the request of the Shadowbornes, thereby being Sharran in nature. Others still allude to strange and clandestine Shadow Magic, set apart from the dire connotations of the Dark Twin's web.

Twinkling like starlight, the jeweled bauble keeps its secrets, much like those who would wear it.

A great ash tree was found growing in an ancient forest. Pure black bark and dark of leaves, its branches were exceptionally useful for the crafting of bows.

However, this practice was cut short when a group of woodcutters were found mysteriously dead under the tree, the bark stained red in their blood.  The black ash tree was soon destroyed in a fit of paranoia afterward, and now only these remain.
This beautiful lion has several large scars, indicating that it is well-accustomed to battle. It stands tall and proud - when it's not sneaking up on anything, that is.
The barracuda is a ray-finned fish known for its large size and fearsome appearance. What this blade has to do with large size is a mystery, but it's looking mean nonetheless.

Kobolds are a cowardly, sadistic race of short humanoids that vigorously contest the human and demi-human races for living space and food. Barely clearing 3 feet in height, kobolds have scaly hides that range from dark, rusty brown to a rusty black. They smell of damp dogs and stagnant water. Their eyes glow like a bright red spark and they have two small horns ranging from tan to white. Because of the kobolds' fondness for wearing raggedy garb of red and orange, their non-prehensile rat-like tails, and their language (which sounds like small dogs yapping), these fell creatures are often not taken seriously. This is often a fatal mistake, for what they lack in size and strength they make up in ferocity and tenacity.
This kobold looks much different from the others...

Its a well known fact that elves are foppish gits, barely able to lift their own swords without a limp-wristed floppy motion. It was for this very reason that these boots were forged. 

The master elven smith Yaldriirmathileh Mastiiramaeviil, spent many long hours making these boots for the elven protectors of the long forgotten court of Myth Drannor. When the kingdom fell, many of these boots were lost, some fell into the hands of those responsible for the fall, others are a prized possession from a dragons hoard. 

Perhaps the adventurer who has stumbled upon them now will use them to serve their intended purpose. Perhaps though, they have simply made another step along the road to obscurity.
This item is not for PC use. If you have somehow come into possession of this, please contact a DM to have it removed and do not use it.

This smooth stone is deceptively unassuming. When used with a command word, it releases a modified antimagic field that can strip a single target of all magical effects. It's very small, and the stone can only be used once. Use it wisely.

A series of documents bearing the seal of the Waterdhavian noble house, Adarbrent. The documents appear to have detailed information about the surrounding area: sea currents, measurements, weather reports, sites with particularly intense magical effects, and map charts. This is probably very important!

A variety of magical tools and instruments that look like they can be used to take measurements or perform experiments. They are accompanied by a seal that suggests they came from an artificer from Candlekeep. These are probably very important!
This sapphire seems to have the power of air! The maker's mark suggests it came from an artificer in Lantan.
This ruby seems to have the power of fire! The maker's mark suggests it came from an artificer in Lantan.
This emerald seems to have the power of earth! The maker's mark suggests it came from an artificer in Lantan.
A beautiful iridescent gem that hums with magic.

Forged of dark alloy and tempered to mirror steel, this tower shield bears a small silver emblem - broken circle crossed by a thin silver line - near its grip. Its face is unmarred by scratches, suggesting its bearer rarely lets his enemies close enough to test it.

Tailored leathers of muted obsidian hue, smooth to the touch and light enough for movement. Subtle silver filigree marks the seams, catching only the faintest light. The attire bears the scent of fine oils and confidence -- the uniform of one who expects to be obeyed without ever raising his voice.

A necklace woven from strands of unicorn hair, freely gifted by a trusted unicorn friend - a token of love and unbreakable trust. Each silken strand has been carefully braided, its faint shimmer a quiet reflection of the bond it represents.

At the center rests a round pendant of polished ivory, its surface delicately carved and encased in a mithral frame adorned with turquoise diamonds and gleaming emeralds. Etched upon the pendant are motifs of an owl and a panther beneath the woven pattern of a dreamcatcher, a symbol of a connection that transcends the ordinary.

On either side of the pendant hangs a small white feather and a tuft of black fur, bound together in devotion. Feather and fur, light and dark, Yin and Yang, each completes the other, and together they form an unshakable bond.

((PnP Spell: Sending, 1/Day. Casting time of 10 minutes applies.))
